description: Nine times out of ten, or maybe 19 times out of 20, these crickets go quiet before I can find them. This one was unusually willing to resume singing. It turns out that small marks on the first two antennal segments can be used to identify species of Oecanthus (Capinera et al. 2004). The marks are visible in the largest version of this photo, but maybe not in their entirety. The thinness of the marks suggests that this could be a four-spotted tree cricket. Two of the original files are short videos of the cricket singing.
